07481nmm a2200781Ia 9781479878840DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814798788407 a10.18574/nyu/9781479878840.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)680921  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0260002bisacsh00aMattering :bFeminism, Science, and Materialism /ced. by Victoria Pitts-Taylor. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBiopolitics ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tMattering Feminism, Science, and Corporeal Politics -- tPart I Probing New Theories of Matter -- t1. Matter in the Shadows: Feminist New Materialism and the Practices of Colonialism -- t2. New Material Feminisms and Historical Materialism: A Diffractive Reading of Two (Ostensibly) Unrelated Perspectives -- t3 On the Politics of “New Feminist Materialisms” -- t4. Nonlinear Evolution, Sexual Difference, and the Ontological Turn: Elizabeth Grosz’s Reading of Darwin -- tPart II Nature/Culture in the Twenty-First Century Sciences -- t5. The Lure of Immateriality in Accounts of Development and Evolution -- t6. Embodying Intersectionality: The Promise (and Peril) of Epigenetics for Feminist Science Studies -- t7 Sex/Gender Matters and Sex/Gender Materialities in the Brain -- t8 The Communicative Phenomenon of Brain-Computer Interfaces -- tPart III Biopolitics and Necropolitics -- t9. Technologies of Failure, Bodies of Resistance: Science, Technology, and the Mechanics of Materializing Marked Bodies -- t10 The Enactment of Intention and Exception through Poisoned Corpses and Toxic Bodies -- t11. Neurofeminism: An Eco-Pharmacology of Childhood ADHD -- t12. Female Bodily (Re)Productivity in the Stem Cell Economy: A Cross-Materialist Feminist Approach -- t13. Prisons Matter: Psychotropics and the Trope of Silence in Technocorrections -- tPart IV New Materialism and Research Practices -- t14. Urban Api-Ethnography: The Matter of Relations between Humans and Honeybees -- t15. Un/Re-making Method: Knowing/Enacting Posthumanist Performative Social Research Methods through ‘Diffractive Genealogies’ and ‘Metaphysical Practices’ -- t16. Experimental Subjects Kick Back: A Provocation for an Alternative Causality in Biomedical Research and Bioethics -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFeminists today are re-imagining nature, biology, and matter in feminist thought and critically addressing new developments in biology, physics, neuroscience, epigenetics and other scientific disciplines. Mattering, edited by noted feminist scholar Victoria Pitts-Taylor, presents contemporary feminist perspectives on the materialist or ‘naturalizing’ turn in feminist theory, and also represents the newest wave of feminist engagement with science. The volume addresses the relationship between human corporeality and subjectivity, questions and redefines the boundaries of human/non-human and nature/culture, elaborates on the entanglements of matter, knowledge, and practice, and addresses biological materialization as a complex and open process. This volume insists that feminist theory can take matter and biology seriously while also accounting for power, taking materialism as a point of departure to rethink key feminist issues. The contributors, an international group of feminist theorists, scientists and scholars, apply concepts in contemporary materialist feminism to examine an array of topics in science, biotechnology, biopolitics, and bioethics. These include neuralplasticity and the brain-machine interface; the use of biometrical identification technologies for transnational border control; epigenetics and the intergenerational transmission of the health effects of social stigma; ADHD and neuropharmacology; and randomized controlled trials of HIV drugs.A unique and interdisciplinary collection, Mattering presents in grounded, concrete terms the need for rethinking disciplinary boundaries and research methodologies in light of the shifts in feminist theorizing and transformations in the sciences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aBarla, Josef, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradley, Kym, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClare, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGabrielson, Teena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGill-Peterson, Julian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHatch, Anthony Ryan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaiser, Anelis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKosut, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMauthner, Natasha S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeißner, Hanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Lisa Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOyama, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPitts-Taylor, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPitts-Taylor, Victoria, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRosengarten, Marsha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoy, Deboleena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmitz, Sigrid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/